-- Banco Compartamos, Telefonos, Usiminas, Vale: Latin America Equity Preview
-- Alexander Cuadros
-- 2010-07-21T03:00:04Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-21/banco-compartamos-telefonos-usiminas-vale-latin-america-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Latin American trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous close.  
 The  MSCI Latin America Index  gained 1.9 percent, the most
in two weeks, to 3,883.42. In Brazil, preferred shares usually
are the most-traded class of stock.  
 Brazil  
 Usinas Siderurgicas de Minas Gerais SA  (USIM5 BS): Brazil’s
second-biggest steelmaker said it plans to raise steel prices
after raw-material costs increased. Prices will rise by 3.5
percent to 6 percent as of Aug. 1, the company said in an e-
mailed statement. Usiminas gained 3.6 percent to 50.48 reais.  
 Vale SA  (VALE5 BS): The United Steelworkers labor union
said talks with Vale at the mining company’s Voisey’s Bay nickel
operations in Canada broke off without a deal. Vale, the world’s
largest iron-ore producer, said in a CNW statement its “very
frustrated and extremely disappointed” with the progress of the
talks. The stock increased 6.2 percent to 40.90 reais.  
 Mexico  
 Banco Compartamos SA  (COMPARTO MM): The Mexican bank that
lends to low-income consumers said second-quarter net income was
477 million pesos. Separately, Chief Executive Officer  Fernando Alvarez Toca  raised the bank’s 2010 growth forecast to 25
percent from 20 percent previously. Compartamos fell 0.1 percent
to 69.99 pesos.  
 Fomento Economico Mexicano SAB  (FEMSAUBD MM): Latin
America’s largest Coca-Cola bottler had its local bond
rating reduced by Moody’s de Mexico to Aa2 from Aa1 after the
company sold its beer unit to Heineken NV earlier this year. The
outlook is stable, Moody’s said. The stock fell 1.1 percent to
57.44 pesos.  
 Telefonos de Mexico SAB  (TELMEXL MM): The nation’s largest
land-line phone company said second-quarter profit fell 40
percent as clients switched to mobile services or cable
providers’ voice plans. Net income dropped to 3.57 billion pesos
($280 million), or 20 centavos a share, from 5.92 billion pesos,
or 32 centavos, a year earlier. The stock rose 0.3 percent to
9.29 pesos.  
